Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Roughly chop the @sun-dried tomatoes{30}, pop into a #small bowl{} and cover with warm water to soften. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced). Trim the @courgette{1} then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a #saucepan{} over medium-high heat (no oil!). When hot, add the courgette pieces and cook stirring occasionally until they begin to soften and char at the edges, ~{3-4%minutes} Meanwhile, zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}(zested and halved). Drain the softened sundried tomatoes.

Once the courgettes have begun to char, add a splash of @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} to the pan and stir in the red onion and sun-dried tomatoes. Cook, stirring until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the garlic and @Peri Peri seasoning{1}. TIP: It's hot, so go easy if you're not a fan! Cook until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

> Peri Peri: The Portuguese marinade so delicious, they named it twice!

Add the @king prawns{150} to the pan. Stir and cook until the prawns are cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle. Meanwhile, pour the boiling @water{240%ml} from your kettle into a #measuring jug{}. Add the @vegetable stock powder{1}. Stir to dissolve.

Stir the @couscous{120} into the saucepan followed by the stock. Pop a #lid{} on the pan or cover tightly with #foil{} and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{8-10%minutes}.

Fluff the couscous up with a #fork{} and stir in the lemon zest and @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Season to taste with lemon juice, @salt{} and @pepper{}. Dig in!